04716nam a22007455i 9780812293456DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20162017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122934567 a10.9783/97808122934562doi  a(DE-B1597)487983  a(OCoLC)1046618940  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aF2532b.G76 2017 7aHIS0370402bisacsh04a981/.0322231 aGroesen, Michiel van, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmsterdam's Atlantic :bPrint Culture and the Making of Dutch Brazil /cMichiel van Groesen. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b51 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Early Modern Americas00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Amsterdam, Dutch Brazil, and the Atlantic World -- tChapter 1. Anticipation -- tChapter 2. Jubilation -- tChapter 3. Appropriation -- tChapter 4. Friction -- tChapter 5. “Amsterdamnified” -- tChapter 6. Recollection -- tConclusion. Toward a Public Atlantic -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1624 the Dutch West India Company established the colony of Brazil. Only thirty years later, the Dutch Republic handed over the colony to Portugal, never to return to the South Atlantic. Because Dutch Brazil was the first sustained Protestant colony in Iberian America, the events there became major news in early modern Europe and shaped a lively print culture.In Amsterdam's Atlantic, historian Michiel van Groesen shows how the rise and tumultuous fall of Dutch Brazil marked the emergence of a "public Atlantic" centered around Holland's capital city. Amsterdam served as Europe's main hub for news from the Atlantic world, and breaking reports out of Brazil generated great excitement in the city, which reverberated throughout the continent. Initially, the flow of information was successfully managed by the directors of the West India Company. However, when Portuguese sugar planters revolted against the Dutch regime, and tales of corruption among leading administrators in Brazil emerged, they lost their hold on the media landscape, and reports traveled more freely. Fueled by the powerful local print media, popular discussions about Brazil became so bitter that the Amsterdam authorities ultimately withdrew their support for the colony.The self-inflicted demise of Dutch Brazil has been regarded as an anomaly during an otherwise remarkably liberal period in Dutch history, and consequently generations of historians have neglected its significance. Amsterdam's Atlantic puts Dutch Brazil back on the front pages and argues that the way the Amsterdam media constructed Atlantic events was a key element in the transformation of public opinion in Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aAmsterdam (Netherlands)xHistoryy17th century. 0aPublic opinionzNetherlandsxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 17th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aEuropean History.  aHA.  aHistory.  aWorld History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831105503060 cprintz978081224866140uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229345640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812293456423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812293456/original  a978-3-11-055030-6  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK